## Countries with an originally European Shared Culture

The term "Western world," or "the West," is a nebulous construct, primarily referring to a collection of nations in [Western Europe](/Western_Europe), [Northern America](/Northern_America), and [Australasia](/Australasia). However, the precise boundaries of this "West" are perpetually debated, with some scholars arguing for the inclusion of [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe) and [Latin America](/Latin_America) based on shared cultural, political, and economic threads. Historically, this concept is often traced back to the foundational civilizations of [Ancient Greece and Rome](/Greco-Roman_world), though this linear projection is not without its critics. The geographical notion of "the West" began to solidify around the 4th century CE when [Constantine the Great](/Constantine_the_Great) divided the [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire) into its [Greek East and Latin West](/Greek_East_and_Latin_West) halves. The [East Roman Empire](/East_Roman_Empire), later known as the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire), persisted for a millennium, while the [West Roman Empire](/West_Roman_Empire) fractured after only about a century and a half. Significant theological and ecclesiastical divergences, culminating in the [Great Schism](/East%E2%80%93West_Schism) of 1054, further cemented a politico-religious divide between the [Western church](/Catholic_Church) and the [Eastern church](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church). The [Crusades](/Crusades), ostensibly aimed at reclaiming trade routes to the East, paradoxically led to the discovery of the [Americas](/Americas) and the subsequent emergence of a "Western" identity, intrinsically linked to [Latin Christendom](/Latin_Church). The earliest recorded use of the term "Western world" dates back to 1586, found in the writings of [William Warner](/William_Warner_(poet)).

The definition of what constitutes the "West" is less about geography and more about the confluence of cultural influences. Nations like [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), despite their location in the [Eastern Hemisphere](/Eastern_Hemisphere), are generally included due to their profound historical ties to the [British](/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland), stemming from [colonization](/First_Fleet) and subsequent European [immigration](/European_Australians). [Russia](/Russia) presents a complex case, sometimes aligned with the West, other times positioned against it, even fostering [anti-Western sentiment](/Anti-Western_sentiment). The ascension of the [United States](/United_States) as a global power, facilitated by advancements in communication and transportation technologies like the [telegraph](/Telegraph) and [railroads](/Rail_transport), further amplified its role in conceptualizations of the West.

Historically, particularly between the 18th and mid-20th centuries, some prominent Western nations such as the United States, Canada, Brazil, Argentina, Australia, and New Zealand were viewed by certain factions as [ethnocracies](/Ethnocracy) designed for [Whites](/Whites). This perspective is often linked to the role of [racism](/Racism) in fueling [Western European colonization](/Analysis_of_European_colonialism_and_colonization) of the [New World](/New_World), which today largely comprises the geographical West, divided between the [Global North and Global South](/Global_North_and_Global_South). In more recent decades, particularly from the late 1960s onwards, parts of the Western world have become significantly more [diverse](/Cultural_diversity) due to [immigration](/Immigration_to_the_Western_world) and evolving [fertility rates](/Total_fertility_rate). The very concept of "the West" has transformed from a mere directional indicator to a complex sociopolitical construct, imbued with notions of progress and modernity, and oriented towards the future.

### Introduction

The roots of Western civilization are deeply embedded in the ancient [Mediterranean world](/History_of_the_Mediterranean_region). [Ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece) and [Ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome) are widely recognized as the cradles of this civilization, with Greece profoundly influencing Rome. Greece's contributions lie in its impact on [philosophy](/Western_philosophy), [democracy](/Democracy), [science](/Ancient_Greece), [aesthetics](/Aesthetics), and architectural principles. Rome, in turn, left an indelible mark on [art](/Western_art), [law](/Law), [warfare](/War), [governance](/Governance), [republicanism](/Republicanism), [engineering](/Roman_engineering), and [religion](/State_church_of_the_Roman_Empire). [Christianity](/Christianity), which became the dominant religion in the West, draws its origins from [Greco](/Ancient_Greek_philosophy)-[Roman](/Ancient_Roman_philosophy) and [Jewish thought](/Jewish_philosophy). The [Christian ethics](/Christian_ethics), informed by the [ethical and moral principles](/Jewish_ethics) of [Judaism](/Judaism), have fundamentally shaped the bedrock of Western societies. Earlier civilizations, such as the [ancient Egyptians](/Ancient_Egypt) and [Mesopotamians](/History_of_Mesopotamia), also played a significant role, contributing advancements in writing, legal systems, and societal organization. The fusion of Greco-Roman and [Judeo-Christian](/Judeo-Christian) influences has led some scholars to characterize Western civilization as a synthesis of [Athens](/Athens) and [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem), or even Athens, Jerusalem, and [Rome](/Rome).

During antiquity, individuals primarily identified with their states, city-states, or empires, rather than as members of a distinct "Western civilization." This specific identification began to crystallize with the rise of Christianity in the [Late Roman Empire](/Later_Roman_Empire). It was during this period that peoples in Europe started to see themselves as part of a unique civilization, differentiating themselves from others, such as [Islam](/Muslim_world). By the [Renaissance](/Renaissance), intellectuals had solidified this concept, linking Western civilization not only to Christianity but also to the intellectual and political achievements of the ancient Greeks and Romans.

Historians like [Carroll Quigley](/Carroll_Quigley), in his work "The Evolution of Civilizations," posit that Western civilization emerged around AD 500, following the [fall of the Western Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire). This collapse, in Quigley's view, created a fertile ground for new ideas that had been suppressed in Classical societies. Regardless of the precise origin, the period between the fall of the Western Roman Empire and the Renaissance witnessed a decline, followed by a significant readaptation, reorientation, and renewed material, technological, and political development in the regions that would later form the core of the "Western sphere." Aspects of [Classical](/Classicism) culture were preserved through the survival of the [Eastern Roman Empire](/Eastern_Roman_Empire) and the influence of the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church). Furthermore, [Arab scholars](/Islamic_contributions_to_Medieval_Europe) played a crucial role in expanding knowledge by transmitting both [Ancient Greco-Roman](/Classical_antiquity) learning and new technologies from India and China to Europe.

[Christopher Columbus](/Christopher_Columbus) [arrives at the New World](/Age_of_Discovery).

From the Renaissance onward, the West evolved beyond its ancient Greco-Roman and Islamic influences, propelled by the [Second Agricultural](/Second_Agricultural_Revolution), [Commercial](/Commercial_Revolution), [Scientific](/Scientific_Revolution), and [Industrial](/Industrial_Revolution) revolutions, which fostered the development of [modern banking](/History_of_banking) concepts. The 18th century's [Age of Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) and the global expansion driven by the [Age of Exploration](/Age_of_Exploration) further elevated the West's prominence. This expansion, often carried out by [Western European](/Western_Europe) colonial powers, was frequently accompanied by [Catholic](/Catholic_missions) [missionaries](/Missionaries) seeking to spread Christianity.

In the modern era, Western culture has continued to transform through the [Renaissance](/Renaissance), the Ages of [Discovery](/Age_of_Exploration) and [Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment), and the Industrial and [Scientific Revolutions](/Scientific_Revolution). The global reach of Western culture was significantly extended through [imperialism](/Imperialism), [colonialism](/Colonialism), and [Christianization](/Christianization) by Western powers from the 15th to the 20th centuries. This influence persists today through the global dissemination of mass culture, a phenomenon often termed [Westernization](/Westernization).

Debates arose in the 1960s regarding the classification of [Latin America](/Latin_America) as a distinct category.

### Culture

*   This section is an excerpt from [Western culture](/Western_culture).

[Leonardo da Vinci](/Leonardo_da_Vinci)'s [Vitruvian Man](/Vitruvian_Man), illustrating the correlation between ideal [human proportions](/Body_proportions) and geometry as described by the ancient Roman architect [Vitruvius](/Vitruvius) in Book III of his treatise [De architectura](/De_architectura).

[Western culture](/Western_culture), also known as Western civilization, European civilization, Occidental culture, Western society, or simply the West, is characterized by its internal diversity. It encompasses the [social norms](/Social_norms), [ethical values](/Ethical_value), [traditional customs](/Tradition), [belief systems](/Belief_systems), [political systems](/Political_system), [artifacts](/Cultural_artifact), and [technologies](/Technology) that are primarily rooted in [European](/History_of_Europe) and [Mediterranean](/History_of_the_Mediterranean_region) histories. As a broad concept, "Western culture" does not adhere to fixed geographical boundaries or a static membership. It generally refers to the classical era cultures of [Ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece), [Ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome), and their subsequent [Christian successors](/Christianity_in_Europe), which spread across the [Mediterranean basin](/Mediterranean_basin) and [Europe](/Europe), and eventually disseminated globally through [colonization](/Colonization) and [globalization](/Globalization).

Historically, scholars have strongly linked the concept of Western culture to the classical period of [Greco-Roman antiquity](/Greco-Roman_antiquity). However, it is also acknowledged that other cultures, such as [Ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt), the [Phoenician city-states](/Phoenicia), and various [Near-Eastern cultures](/Near_East), provided stimulation and influence. The [Hellenistic period](/Hellenistic_period) was particularly important for promoting [syncretism](/Syncretism), blending Greek, Roman, and Jewish traditions. Significant advancements in literature, engineering, and science shaped the [Hellenistic Jewish](/Hellenistic_Judaism) culture from which emerged the [earliest Christians](/Jewish_Christianity) and the Greek [New Testament](/New_Testament). The eventual [Christianization](/Christianization) of Europe in [late-antiquity](/Late_antiquity) ensured that [Christianity](/Christianity), particularly the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church), remained a dominant force in Western culture for many centuries.

Western culture continued to evolve through the Middle Ages, influenced by the [medieval renaissances](/Medieval_renaissances), the significant contributions of the [Islamic world](/Islamic_world_contributions_to_Medieval_Europe) via [Al-Andalus](/Al-Andalus) and [Sicily](/Emirate_of_Sicily) (including the transfer of technology from the East and [Latin translations](/Latin_translations_of_the_12th_century) of [Arabic texts on science](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world) and [philosophy](/Early_Islamic_philosophy)), and the [Italian Renaissance](/Italian_Renaissance). The arrival of [Greek scholars](/Greek_scholars_in_the_Renaissance) fleeing the [fall of Constantinople](/Fall_of_Constantinople) reintroduced ancient Greek and Roman texts to central and western Europe. [Medieval Christianity](/History_of_Christianity_during_the_Middle_Ages) is credited with the establishment of the modern [university](/University), the modern hospital system, advancements in scientific economics, and the development of [natural law](/Natural_law), which would later inform [international law](/International_law). European culture developed a rich tapestry of philosophy, [medieval scholasticism](/Scholasticism), [mysticism](/Mysticism), and both [Christian](/Christian_humanism) and [secular humanism](/Secular_humanism), setting the stage for the [Protestant Reformation](/Reformation) in the 16th century. Led by figures like [Martin Luther](/Martin_Luther), Protestantism challenged the authority of the Catholic Church and championed ideas of [individual freedom](/Individual_freedom) and [religious reform](/Religious_reform), laying the groundwork for modern concepts of [personal responsibility](/Personal_responsibility) and governance.

The [Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) in the 17th and 18th centuries placed a strong emphasis on [reason](/Reason), [science](/Science), and [individual rights](/Individual_rights), profoundly influencing [revolutions](/Age_of_Revolution) across Europe and the Americas and the development of modern democratic institutions. Enlightenment thinkers promoted ideals of [political pluralism](/Pluralism_(political_philosophy)) and [empirical inquiry](/Empiricism), which, alongside the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), transformed Western society. The influence of Enlightenment [rationalism](/Rationalism) continued into the 19th and 20th centuries with the rise of [secularism](/Secularism) and [liberal democracy](/Liberal_democracy), while the Industrial Revolution fueled unprecedented economic and technological growth. Significant cultural shifts were marked by the expansion of [civil rights](/Civil_rights_movements) and the [decline of religious authority](/Secularization). Key tendencies defining modern Western societies include the concept of [political pluralism](/Pluralism_(political_philosophy)), [individualism](/Individualism), the prominence of [subcultures](/Subcultures) or [countercultures](/Counterculture), and increasing cultural [syncretism](/Syncretism) resulting from [globalization](/Globalization) and [immigration](/Immigration_to_the_Western_world).

