#### The West of the Mediterranean Region During Antiquity

The geopolitical divisions within Europe that gave rise to the concept of East and West can be traced back to the [ancient](/Classical_antiquity) tyrannical and imperialistic [Graeco-Roman](/Graeco-Roman) era. The Eastern [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_Sea) was home to highly urbanized cultures that shared [Greek](/Greek_language) as their common tongue, a legacy of [Alexander the Great](/Alexander_the_Great) and his [Hellenistic successors](/Diadochi). In contrast, the West was considerably more rural and adopted Latin as its primary language. Following the fall of the [Western Roman Empire](/Western_Roman_Empire) and the advent of the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages), Western and Central Europe became largely isolated from the East. In the East, [Byzantine](/Byzantine_Empire) Greek culture and [Eastern Christianity](/Eastern_Christianity) became foundational influences for Eastern European populations, particularly the East and South Slavic peoples. [Citation needed]

The main travels of the [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery) (beginning in the 15th century)

[Roman Catholic](/Roman_Catholic) Western and Central Europe thus maintained a distinct identity, particularly as it began to redevelop during the Renaissance. Even following the Protestant [Reformation](/Reformation), Protestant Europe continued to see itself as more tied to Roman Catholic Europe than other parts of the perceived "civilized world". The use of the term "West" as a specific cultural and geopolitical term developed over the course of the [Age of Exploration](/Age_of_Exploration) as Europe expanded its culture globally. Roman Catholics were the first major religious group to migrate to the [New World](/New_World), with settlers in the colonies of [Spain](/Spanish_Empire) and [Portugal](/Portuguese_Empire) (and later, [France](/French_colonial_empire)) belonging to that faith. [English](/British_Empire) and [Dutch](/Dutch_Empire) colonies, on the other hand, tended to be more religiously diverse. Settlers to these colonies included [Anglicans](/Anglican), Dutch [Calvinists](/Calvinists), English [Puritans](/Puritans) and other [nonconformists](/Nonconformist_(Protestantism)), [English Catholics](/Maryland_Toleration_Act), Scottish [Presbyterians](/Presbyterian), French [Huguenots](/Huguenot), German and Swedish [Lutherans](/Lutherans), as well as [Quakers](/Quakers), [Mennonites](/Mennonites), [Amish](/Amish), and [Moravians](/Moravian_Church). [Citation needed]

#### Ancient Roman World (6th Century BC – AD 395–476)

*   Main articles: [Roman Republic](/Roman_Republic), [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire), and [Fall of the Western Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire)

The [Roman Republic](/Roman_Republic) in 218 BC, after conquering most of the Italian Peninsula, stood on the precipice of its most successful and devastating war against the [Carthaginians](/Carthaginians).

Graphical map of the post-AD 395 [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire), highlighting the differences between the western [Roman Catholic](/Roman_Catholic) and eastern [Greek Orthodox](/Greek_Orthodox) parts, on the eve of the death of the last emperor to rule both the [western](/Western_Roman_Empire) and [eastern](/Eastern_Roman_Empire) halves. The concept of "East-West" originated in the cultural division between [Christian](/Christianity) Churches. [Citation needed] The [Western](/Western_Roman_Empire) and [Eastern](/Eastern_Roman_Empire) Roman Empires on the eve of the Western collapse in September AD 476.

The [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire) in AD 117. Over 350 years, the Roman Republic transformed into an Empire, expanding its territory twenty-fivefold.

[Ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome) (6th century BC – AD 476) refers to the ancient [Roman society](/Roman_society) that conquered Central Italy, assimilating the Italian [Etruscan culture](/Villanovan_culture). Originating from the [Latium](/Latium) region around the 8th century BC, it grew into a vast empire that straddled the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea). Throughout its 10-century territorial expansion, [Roman civilization](/Roman_civilization) evolved from a small [monarchy](/Monarchy) (753–509 BC) to a [republic](/Roman_Republic) (509–27 BC), and finally to an [autocratic](/Autocracy) empire (27 BC – AD 476). Its empire came to dominate Western, Central, and Southeastern Europe, North Africa, and, as an autocratic empire, a vast [Middle Eastern](/Middle_Eastern) territory until its end. Conquest was achieved through the might of the [Roman legions](/Roman_legions) and subsequently through [cultural assimilation](/Cultural_assimilation) by granting privileges of Roman citizenship. Despite its immense legacy, a confluence of factors led to the eventual decline and fall of the [Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Roman_Empire). [Citation needed]

The [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire) succeeded the [Roman Republic](/Roman_Republic), which had endured for approximately 500 years (c. 510–30 BC). In 350 years, from the successful and devastating [war](/Second_Punic_War) with the [Phoenicians](/Phoenicia) beginning in 218 BC to the reign of [Emperor Hadrian](/Emperor_Hadrian) by AD 117, ancient Rome expanded its territory twenty-fivefold. An equivalent amount of time passed before its fall in AD 476. Rome's expansion predated the empire's zenith, which was marked by the conquest of [Dacia](/Dacia) in AD 106 (modern-day [Romania](/Romania)) under Emperor Trajan. At its territorial peak, the Roman Empire encompassed approximately 5,000,000 square kilometers (1,900,000 sq mi) and a population of 100 million. From the era of Caesar (100–44 BC) to the Fall of the Western Roman Empire, Rome exerted dominion over [Southern Europe](/Southern_Europe), the Mediterranean coast of [Northern Africa](/Northern_Africa), and the [Levant](/Levant), including ancient trade [routes](/Amber_Road) and populations beyond its borders. Ancient Rome's contributions to law, warfare, art, literature, architecture, technology, and language in the Western world are immense, and its [history](/History_of_Rome) continues to exert a significant global influence. The [Latin language](/Latin_language) served as the foundation for the evolution of [Romance languages](/Romance_languages) and remained the official language of the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) and all its ceremonies throughout Europe until 1967. It also served as an official or co-official language in countries like Italy and Poland from the 9th to the 18th centuries. [Citation needed]

Ending [invasions](/Migration_Period) on the Roman Empire from the 2nd through the 5th centuries, establishing mostly [Germanic kingdoms](/Germanic_kingdoms) in its place.

In AD 395, mere decades before its collapse in the West, the Roman Empire was formally divided into a [Western](/Western_Roman_Empire) and an [Eastern](/Eastern_Roman_Empire) entity, each with its own emperors, capitals, and governments, though ostensibly they remained part of a single formal Empire. The provinces of the [Western Roman Empire](/Western_Roman_Empire) were eventually supplanted by [Northern European](/Northern_European) [Germanic](/Germanic_peoples)-ruled kingdoms in the 5th century, a consequence of [civil wars, corruption, and devastating Germanic invasions](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire) by tribes such as the [Huns](/Huns), [Goths](/Goths), [Franks](/Franks), and [Vandals](/Vandals) during their late [expansion](/Migration_period) across Europe. The Visigoths' three-day [AD 410 sack of Rome](/Sack_of_Rome_(410)), occurring shortly after their raids in Greece, was a shocking event, marking the first time in nearly 800 years that Rome had fallen to a foreign enemy. [St. Jerome](/Jerome), then residing in Bethlehem, lamented, "The City which had taken the whole world was itself taken." This was followed by the [sack of AD 455](/Sack_of_Rome_(455)), which lasted 14 days and was carried out by the [Vandals](/Vandals). The eternal spirit of Rome endured through the [Holy See of Rome](/Holy_See_of_Rome) (the [Latin Church](/Latin_Church)) for centuries to come. The ancient [Barbarian](/Barbarian) tribes, often comprised of Roman-trained soldiers paid to guard the empire's extensive borders, had evolved into militarily sophisticated "Romanized barbarians." They ruthlessly conquered Roman territories and plundered their possessions. [Citation needed]

The Roman Empire is the historical context from which the idea of "the West" began to emerge. [Note f]

The [Eastern Roman Empire](/Eastern_Roman_Empire), governed from [Constantinople](/Constantinople), is typically referred to as the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) after AD 476, the traditional date marking the fall of the Roman Empire and the commencement of the [Early Middle Ages](/Early_Middle_Ages). The survival of the Eastern Roman Empire preserved Roman legal and cultural traditions, blending them with Greek and Christian elements for another thousand years. The designation "Byzantine Empire" was adopted centuries later, after its demise. The dissolution of the Western half, officially ending in AD 476, was in reality a protracted process that concluded with the rise of Catholic [Gaul](/Gaul) (modern-day [France](/France)), with its effective rule beginning around AD 800. Only the Eastern Roman Empire remained. The Eastern half continued to identify itself as the Roman Empire, with its inhabitants calling themselves Romans, as the term "Roman" was meant to signify all [Christians](/Christians). Pope crowned [Charlemagne](/Charlemagne) as [Emperor of the Romans](/Holy_Roman_Emperor) of the newly established [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire), leading to the West conceptualizing itself as comprising Western Latins inhabiting the old Western Empire, and Eastern Greeks (those within the Roman remnant of the old Eastern Empire). [Citation needed]

#### The Birth of the European West During the Middle Ages

