In the early 4th century, the locus of power was divided between two distinct imperial legacies within the Roman Empire: the older [Aegean Sea](/Aegean_Sea) [Greek](/Greece) heritage (of [Classical Greece](/Classical_Greece)) in the Eastern Mediterranean, and the newer, highly successful [Tyrrhenian Sea](/Tyrrhenian_Sea) [Latin](/Latin) heritage (of [Ancient Latium and Tuscany](/Etruria)) in the Western Mediterranean. A pivotal moment occurred when [Constantine the Great](/Constantine_the_Great) chose to establish [Constantinople](/Constantinople) (modern-day [Istanbul](/Istanbul)) in [Turkey](/Turkey) as the "New Rome," making it the capital of his Empire (later termed the "[Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire)" by modern historians) in AD 330.

The [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) in AD 1025, prior to the Christian [East-West Schism](/East-West_Schism).

This internal conflict of legacies may have originated as early as the [assassination of Julius Caesar](/Assassination_of_Julius_Caesar) three centuries prior, when the Roman Republic transitioned into the "Roman Empire." It reached its apex during the numerous [civil wars](/List_of_Roman_civil_wars_and_revolts) of the 3rd century. This was also the period when the [Huns](/Huns), a group of ancient Eastern European tribes designated as barbarians by the Romans, migrated from modern-day [Hungary](/Hungary) into the [Dalmatia](/Dalmatia) (modern-day [Croatia](/Croatia)) region. Over the subsequent 150 years, this contributed to the official division of the Roman Empire into two halves. It was also a time of formal acceptance of Christianity as the Empire's [religious](/Religion) policy, with emperors actively suppressing and combating previous [pagan religions](/Pagan_religion).

History of the spread of Christianity: in AD 325 (dark blue) and AD 600 (blue), following the collapse of the Western Roman Empire under [Germanic migrations](/Germanic_migration).

The Eastern Roman Empire encompassed territories south-west of the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), bordering the [Eastern Mediterranean](/Eastern_Mediterranean) and parts of the [Adriatic Sea](/Adriatic_Sea). This division into Eastern and Western Roman Empires later influenced the administrative structures of the [Roman Catholic and Eastern Greek Orthodox](/Greek_East_and_Latin_West) churches, leading to disputes between Rome and Constantinople over which city held primacy as the capital of [Western religion](/Catholicity). [Citation needed]

As the [Eastern (Orthodox)](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church) and Western (Catholic) churches expanded their influence, the dividing line between Eastern and Western Christianity shifted. This movement was affected by the influence of the Byzantine Empire and the fluctuating power and influence of the Catholic Church in Rome. The geographic line of religious division roughly mirrored a [cultural divide](/Cultural_divide). [Citation needed]

Rise of the [Germanic](/Germanic_people) [Frankish Empire](/Frankish_Empire) before [Charlemagne's coronation](/Coronation_of_the_Holy_Roman_Emperor) in Rome.

In AD 800, under [Charlemagne](/Charlemagne), the [Early Medieval](/Early_Medieval) Franks established an empire recognized by the [Pope](/Pope) in Rome as the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire). This entity, a revival of the ancient Roman Empire under perpetual Germanic rule from AD 962, inherited the prestige of the Roman Empire but offended the [Eastern Roman Emperor](/Eastern_Roman_Emperor) in Constantinople. This animosity contributed to the [Crusades](/Crusades) and the [East–West Schism](/East%E2%80%93West_Schism). The Pope's coronation of the Emperor established the assumption of supreme papal authority, the [papal hierarchy](/History_of_the_Papacy), as the ultimate spiritual power, thereby defining the civilization of [Western Christendom](/Christendom) until the Protestant Reformation. [Citation needed]

The earliest conceptualization of Europe as a cultural sphere, rather than simply a geographic term, is attributed to [Alcuin of York](/Alcuin_of_York) during the [Carolingian Renaissance](/Carolingian_Renaissance) in the 9th century. However, this concept was initially confined to the territories practicing [Western Christianity](/Western_Christianity).

The [Latin Church](/Latin_Church) of western and central Europe formally separated from the eastern [Greek](/Eastern_Orthodoxy) patriarchates in the Christian [East–West Schism](/East%E2%80%93West_Schism), also known as the "Great Schism," during the [Gregorian Reforms](/Gregorian_Reforms) (which sought to centralize the authority of the Roman Catholic Church) in April 1054, three months after the death of [Pope Leo IX](/Pope_Leo_IX). [Citation needed] Following the 1054 [Great Schism](/East%E2%80%93West_Schism), both the [Western](/Western_Christianity) Church and the [Eastern](/Eastern_Orthodoxy) Church continued to consider themselves uniquely orthodox and catholic. [Augustine](/Augustine) wrote in *On True Religion*: "Religion is to be sought... only among those who are called Catholic or orthodox Christians, that is, guardians of truth and followers of right." [Citation needed] Over time, [Western Christianity](/Western_Christianity) gradually adopted the "Catholic" label, and people in Western Europe increasingly associated the "Orthodox" label with [Eastern Christianity](/Eastern_Christianity) (though in some languages, the term "Catholic" is not exclusively tied to the Western Church). This distinction emerged despite both "Catholic" and "Orthodox" being used as ecclesiastical adjectives as early as the 2nd and 4th centuries, respectively. Concurrently, the reach of both Christendoms expanded. The Western Church converted Germanic peoples, Bohemia, Poland, Hungary, Scandinavia, Finnic peoples, Baltic peoples, the British Isles, and other previously non-Christian lands in the northwest. Meanwhile, the [Eastern Orthodox Church](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church) converted Eastern Slavic peoples, Bulgaria, Serbia, Montenegro, Russian territories, [Vlachs](/Vlachs), and Georgia. [Citation needed]

The Byzantine Empire in AD 1180, before the Latin [Fourth Crusade](/Fourth_Crusade).

In 1071, the Byzantine army suffered a defeat against the [Muslim](/Muslim) [Turco-Persians](/Turco-Persian) of medieval [Asia](/Asia), resulting in the loss of most of [Asia Minor](/Asia_Minor). This posed a grave threat to the future of the [Eastern Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodoxy) [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire). The Emperor appealed to the [Pope](/Papacy) in Rome for military assistance to reclaim the lost territories for Christian rule. This appeal led to a series of military campaigns by Western European forces into the eastern Mediterranean, known as the Crusades. Unfortunately for the Byzantines, the crusaders, drawn from the nobility of France, German territories, the Low Countries, England, and Italy, owed no allegiance to the Byzantine Emperor and established their own states in the conquered regions, [including the heart of the Byzantine Empire](/Fourth_Crusade).

The Holy Roman Empire would [dissolve](/Dissolution_of_the_Holy_Roman_Empire) on 6 August 1806, following the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution) and the establishment of the [Confederation of the Rhine](/Confederation_of_the_Rhine) by [Napoleon](/Napoleon).

The Greek Byzantine Empire, divided by the newly established [Latin Crusader State](/Latin_Empire) after the Fourth Crusade (shown partially in Greece and partially in Turkey).

The [decline of the Byzantine Empire](/Decline_of_the_Byzantine_Empire) (13th–15th centuries) was significantly impacted by the Latin [Fourth Crusade](/Fourth_Crusade) of AD 1202–04, an event considered pivotal in solidifying the [schism](/East-West_Schism) between the [Christian](/Christianity) churches of the [Greek](/Greek_language) [Byzantine Rite](/Byzantine_Rite) and the [Latin](/Latin_language) [Roman Rite](/Roman_Rite). An [anti-Western riot](/Massacre_of_the_Latins) targeting Latins erupted in [Constantinople](/Constantinople) in 1182. The exceedingly wealthy [Venetians](/Republic_of_Venice), particularly after previous [Crusades](/Crusades), successfully maintained control over the coast of [Catholic](/Catholic_Church) present-day Croatia (specifically [Dalmatia](/Dalmatia)), a region of strategic interest to the [maritime](/Maritime_Republic) medieval Venetian Republic's financiers and their rivals, such as the Republic of Genoa, who were rebelling against Venetian economic dominance. [Citation needed] What followed was an irrevocable blow to the already weakened Byzantine Empire: the [Crusader army's sack of Constantinople](/Siege_of_Constantinople_(1204)) in April 1204. This sack of the capital of the [Greek Christian](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church)-controlled [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) is described as one of the most profitable and disgraceful sacks of a city in history. [Citation needed] This event paved the way for Muslim conquests in [present-day Turkey](/Anatolia) and the [Balkans](/Balkans) in the subsequent centuries, with only a handful of Crusaders continuing to their original destination in the [Holy Land](/Crusader_states). The Balkans, historically a cultural crossroads, served as a juncture between the [Latin](/Latin) and [Greek](/Greek_language) spheres of the [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire). It was also the destination of a massive influx of pagan (meaning "non-Christians") [Bulgars](/Bulgars) and [Slavs](/Slavs), an area where [Catholic](/Catholic) and [Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church) Christianity met, [Citation needed] as well as a meeting point between [Islam](/Islam) and Christianity. The [Papal Inquisition](/Papal_Inquisition) was established on a permanent basis in AD 1229, managed largely by clergymen in Rome, [Citation needed] and was abolished six centuries later. Prior to AD 1100, the [Catholic Church suppressed](/Catholic_Inquisition) what it deemed heresy, primarily through ecclesiastical proscription or imprisonment, but without recourse to torture [Citation needed] and rarely resorting to executions. [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed]

[Martin Luther](/Martin_Luther), [Protestant](/Protestantism) [Reformer](/Reformation).

This highly profitable [Central European](/Central_Europe) Fourth Crusade indirectly prompted the 14th-century [Renaissance](/Renaissance_Italy) (meaning 'Rebirth') in the [Italian city-states](/Italian_city-states), including the [Papal States](/Papal_States). This preceded the Protestant Reformation and the [Counter-Reformation](/Counter-Reformation) (which established the [Roman Inquisition](/Roman_Inquisition) to succeed the [Medieval Inquisition](/Medieval_Inquisition)). Subsequently, the discovery of the American continent led to the dissolution of West Christendom as even a theoretical unified political body. This culminated in the religious [Eighty Years' War](/Eighty_Years_War) (1568–1648) and the [Thirty Years' War](/Thirty_Years_War) (1618–1648) between [various Protestant and Catholic states](/List_of_states_in_the_Holy_Roman_Empire) within the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire), and the emergence of [religiously diverse](/Protestantism) [confessions](/Criticism_of_the_Catholic_Church). Within this context, the Protestant Reformation (1517) can be viewed as a schism within the Catholic Church. German monk [Martin Luther](/Martin_Luther), building on the work of predecessors, broke with the Pope and the Emperor over the Catholic Church's corrupt commercialization of [indulgences](/Indulgences) in the [Late Medieval Period](/Late_Medieval_Period). Backed by many German princes and aided by the development of the [printing press](/Printing_press), Luther sought to reform corruption within the Church. [Citation needed]

Both of these religious wars concluded with the [Peace of Westphalia](/Peace_of_Westphalia) (1648), which enshrined the concept of the [nation-state](/Nation-state) and the principle of absolute [national sovereignty](/National_sovereignty) in [international law](/International_law). As European influence spread across the globe, these [Westphalian principles](/Westphalian_sovereignty), particularly the notion of sovereign states, became foundational to international law and the prevailing world order.

### Expansion of the West: The Era of Colonialism (15th–20th Centuries)

*   Main articles: [New World](/New_World), [Analysis of Western European colonialism and colonization](/Analysis_of_Western_European_colonialism_and_colonization), [Mercantilism](/Mercantilism), and [Imperialism](/Imperialism)
*   This section needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Please assist in improving this article by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (November 2021) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

[Portuguese discoveries](/Portuguese_discoveries) and explorations since 1336: first arrival locations and dates; main Portuguese [spice trade](/Spice_trade) routes in the [Indian Ocean](/Indian_Ocean) (blue); [territories claimed](/Portuguese_empire) by [King John III of Portugal](/King_John_III_of_Portugal) (c. 1536) (green).
Apex of the [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire) in 1790.

In the 13th and 14th centuries, numerous European travelers, many of them Christian [missionaries](/Missionary), sought to establish trade relations with Asia and [Africa](/Africa). The Crusades coincided with a relative contraction of the Orthodox [Byzantine](/Byzantine_silk)'s large silk industry [in favor of Catholic Western Europe](/History_of_silk) and the rise of the [Western Papacy](/Papal_States). The most renowned of these [merchant travelers](/Chronology_of_European_exploration_of_Asia) pursuing [East–west trade](/Spice_trade) was the Venetian [Marco Polo](/Marco_Polo). However, these journeys had limited lasting impact on East-West trade due to a series of political shifts in Asia in the final decades of the 14th century, which curtailed further European exploration of the continent. Specifically, the new [Ming](/Ming_dynasty) rulers were unreceptive to religious proselytism by European missionaries and merchants. Simultaneously, the [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Empire) [Turks](/Turkish_people) consolidated their control over the eastern [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_Sea), effectively blocking key overland trade routes. [Citation needed]

The [Portuguese](/Kingdom_of_Portugal) led the charge in discovering oceanic routes that would provide more cost-effective and accessible access to South and East Asian goods, facilitated by advancements in maritime technology such as the [caravel](/Caravel) ship introduced in the mid-1400s. The charting of oceanic routes between East and West commenced with the groundbreaking voyages of Portuguese and [Spanish](/Kingdom_of_Spain) sea captains. In 1492, [European colonialism](/European_colonialism) expanded globally with the [exploring voyage](/Voyages_of_Christopher_Columbus) of merchant, navigator, and colonizer [Christopher Columbus](/Christopher_Columbus). These expeditions were influenced by medieval European adventurers who had journeyed overland to the Far East in pursuit of the [spice trade](/Spice_trade) with Asia, contributing to the geographical understanding of parts of the Asian continent. They hold immense significance in [Western history](/History_of_Western_civilization) as they marked the inception of European exploration, [colonization](/Colonization), and exploitation of the [American continents](/Americas) and their [native inhabitants](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas). [Note g] [Note h] The [European colonization of the Americas](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas) led to the [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade) between the 1490s and the 1800s, which also fueled intertribal warfare in Africa and the development of racist ideologies. Prior to the abolition of its slave trade in 1807, the [British Empire](/British_Empire) alone (which initiated colonial efforts in 1578, nearly a century after the Portuguese and Spanish empires) was responsible for transporting 3.5 million African slaves to the Americas, representing one-third of all slaves transported across the Atlantic. [Citation needed] The [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire) was dissolved in 1806 by the [French Revolutionary Wars](/French_Revolutionary_Wars); the abolition of the [Roman Catholic Inquisition](/Roman_Catholic_Inquisition) followed. [Citation needed]

Through the extensive reach of these empires, Western institutions were disseminated worldwide. This process of influence (and imposition) began with the [voyages of discovery](/Age_of_Discovery), the [colonization, conquest, and exploitation](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas) by [Portugal](/Portuguese_Empire), enforced by [papal bulls](/Papal_bull) in the 1450s (following the [fall of the Byzantine Empire](/Fall_of_the_Byzantine_Empire)), granting Portugal a monopoly on navigation, warfare, and trade in newly discovered lands, [Citation needed] and the competitive voyages of [Spanish](/Spanish_Empire) navigators. It continued with the rise of the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company) after the destabilizing Spanish [discovery of the New World](/Discovery_of_the_New_World), and the establishment and expansion of the [English](/British_Empire) and [French](/French_colonial_empire) colonial empires, among others. [Citation needed] Even after demands for self-determination from the peoples within Western empires led to [decolonization](/Decolonization), these institutions persisted. A notable example is the requirement for [post-colonial](/Postcolonialism) societies to form nation-states modeled on the Western tradition. This often resulted in arbitrary boundaries and borders that did not accurately represent entire nations, peoples, or cultures (as seen in much of Africa), frequently leading to international conflicts and friction to this day. While not strictly part of the Western colonization process, Western culture, following the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages), did penetrate other global cultures during the colonial period of the 15th–20th centuries. [Citation needed] Historically, [colonialism](/Colonialism) was often justified by the values of [individualism](/Individualism) and [enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment). [Citation needed]

The concepts of a world comprised of [nation-states](/Nation-states), originating from the [Peace of Westphalia](/Peace_of_Westphalia) in 1648, coupled with the ideologies of the Enlightenment, the advent of [modernity](/Modernity), the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution) [Citation needed] and the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), [Citation needed] produced profound social transformations and political and [economic](/History_of_banking) institutions that have influenced (or been imposed upon) most nations globally today. Historians generally agree that the Industrial Revolution stands as one of history's most significant events. [Citation needed]

The span of [three centuries](/Early_modern_period) since Christopher Columbus' late 15th-century voyages, encompassing the [deportation of slaves](/Atlantic_slave_trade) [from Africa](/Slavery_in_the_colonial_history_of_the_United_States) and the dominant northern-[Atlantic](/Atlantic) position of the [British](/British_Isles), later evolved into the modern-day [United States of America](/United_States_of_America). This evolution culminated with the ratification of the [Constitution of the United States](/Constitution_of_the_United_States) by [thirteen States](/History_of_the_United_States_Constitution) on the North American [East Coast](/East_Coast_of_the_United_States) before the end of the 18th century.

#### Enlightenment (17th–18th Centuries)

*   Main articles: [Age of Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) and [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution)

[Eric Voegelin](/Eric_Voegelin) characterized the 18th century as a period where "the sentiment grows that one age has come to its close and that a new age of Western civilization is about to be born." According to Voegelin, the Enlightenment, also known as the [Age of Reason](/Age_of_Reason), represents the "atrophy of Christian transcendental experiences and [seeks] to enthrone the [Newtonian](/Isaac_Newton) method of science as the only valid method of arriving at truth." [Citation needed] Its intellectual precursors included [John Milton](/John_Milton) and [Baruch Spinoza](/Baruch_Spinoza). [Citation needed] Milton's encounter with [Galileo](/Galileo) in 1638 profoundly influenced him, leading to his seminal work [Areopagitica](/Areopagitica), where he warned against the imposition of "an undeserved thraldom upon learning" by inquisitorial forces, advocating for [free speech](/Free_speech). [Citation needed]

Key achievements of the 17th century included the invention of the [telescope](/Telescope) and the widespread acceptance of [heliocentrism](/Heliocentrism). 18th-century scholars continued to refine [Newton's theory of gravitation](/Newton%27s_theory_of_gravitation), with notable contributions from [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler), [Pierre Louis Maupertuis](/Pierre_Louis_Maupertuis), [Alexis-Claude Clairaut](/Alexis-Claude_Clairaut), [Jean Le Rond d'Alembert](/Jean_Le_Rond_d%27Alembert), [Joseph-Louis Lagrange](/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange), and [Pierre-Simon de Laplace](/Pierre-Simon_Laplace). Laplace's five-volume [Treatise on Celestial Mechanics](/Trait%C3%A9_de_m%C3%A9canique_c%C3%A9leste) is considered a landmark work of 18th-century Newtonianism. [Astronomy](/Astronomy) gained significant prestige, with governments funding new observatories and the development of more powerful telescopes leading to the discovery of new planets, [asteroids](/Asteroids), [nebulae](/Nebulae), and [comets](/Comet). These advancements also improved [navigation](/Navigation) and [cartography](/Cartography). Astronomy emerged as the second most popular scientific profession, following [medicine](/Medicine). [Citation needed]

A prevalent meta-narrative of the Enlightenment is the "secularization theory," which posits modernity as a complete break from the past, championing innovation and science as inherently good and embodying modern values of [rationalism](/Rationalism), while relegating faith to superstition and traditionalism. [Citation needed] Inspired by the Scientific Revolution, the Enlightenment championed ideals of progress and improvement. [Descartes](/Descartes) and [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton) were revered as exemplars of human intellectual achievement. [Condorcet](/Condorcet), in his *Sketch of the Progress of the Human Mind* (1794), outlined humanity's progress from [primitive society](/Urgesellschaft) through [agrarianism](/Agrarianism), the invention of writing and the [printing press](/Printing_press), to an era where "the Sciences and Philosophy threw off the Yoke of Authority." [Citation needed]

The French writer [Pierre Bayle](/Pierre_Bayle) controversially denounced Spinoza as a [pantheist](/Pantheist), implying atheism, a critique that garnered significant attention for Spinoza. The pantheism controversy of the late 18th century saw [Gotthold Lessing](/Gotthold_Lessing) attacked by [Friedrich Heinrich Jacobi](/Friedrich_Heinrich_Jacobi) for his support of Spinoza's pantheism. Lessing was defended by [Moses Mendelssohn](/Moses_Mendelssohn), who, while not fully endorsing pantheism, aligned with [Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz) in arguing that God and the world were not of the same substance. Spinoza was excommunicated from the Dutch [Sephardic](/Sephardic) community, yet for Jewish individuals seeking secular guidance, Spinoza held as much importance as Voltaire and Kant. [Citation needed]

#### 19th Century

In the early 19th century, the systematic process of [urbanization](/Urbanization) began, marked by migration from rural areas to manufacturing centers, leading to a surge in town populations. Global population also rose, estimated to have reached one billion in 1804. [Citation needed] Concurrently, the philosophical movement that would become known as [Romanticism](/Romanticism) emerged, following the preceding Age of [Reason](/17th-century_philosophy) in the 1600s and the [Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) of the 1700s. These intellectual currents are considered to have fostered the sustained economic development of the 19th-century Western world. [Citation needed] Prior to the widespread urbanization and industrialization of the 1800s, demand for [oriental](/Orientalism) goods such as [porcelain](/Porcelain), [silk](/Silk), [spices](/Spice), and [tea](/Tea) remained a primary driver of European imperialism in Asia. With the notable exception of the British East India Company's rule in India, European engagement in Asia was largely confined to trading posts and strategic outposts necessary for protecting commerce. [Citation needed] [Industrialization](/Industrialisation), however, dramatically amplified European demand for Asian raw materials. The severe Long Depression of the 1870s intensified the quest for new markets for European industrial products and financial services in Africa, the Americas, Eastern Europe, and particularly in Asia. Western powers, for instance, exploited their advantages in [China](/China) through the [Opium Wars](/Opium_Wars). [Citation needed] This led to "[New Imperialism](/New_Imperialism)," characterized by a shift from trade and [indirect rule](/Indirect_rule) to the formal colonial control of vast overseas territories, administered as political extensions of their mother countries. [Citation needed] The latter decades of the 19th century witnessed a transition from "informal imperialism" ([hegemony](/Hegemony)) [Note i] achieved through military influence and economic dominance, to direct rule—a resurgence of colonial [imperialism](/Imperialism)—in the [African continent](/African_continent) and the [Middle East](/Middle_East). [Citation needed]

During the socioeconomically optimistic and innovative decades of the [Second Industrial Revolution](/Second_Industrial_Revolution) (roughly 1870s–1914), also known as the "[Belle Époque](/Belle_Époque)", established colonial powers in Asia, including the United Kingdom, France, and the Netherlands, expanded their empires to include vast territories in the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent) and [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia). Japan, during the [Meiji period](/Meiji_period) (1868–1912), also engaged in similar expansionist activities, building upon earlier interactions with Portuguese, Spanish, and Dutch traders. The [Japanese Empire](/Empire_of_Japan) recognized the strategic importance of European nations. Traditional Japanese society transformed into an industrial and militarist power, mirroring Western empires like the [British Empire](/British_Empire) and the [French Third Republic](/French_Third_Republic), as well as the [German Empire](/German_Empire). [Verification needed] [Citation needed]

At the conclusion of the [Spanish–American War](/Spanish%E2%80%93American_War) in 1898, the [Philippines](/Philippines), [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico), [Guam](/Guam), and [Cuba](/Cuba) were ceded to the [United States](/United_States) under the terms of the [Treaty of Paris](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1898)). The U.S. rapidly emerged as a new imperial power in [East Asia](/East_Asia) and the [Pacific Ocean area](/Pacific_Ocean). The Philippines continued its struggle against colonial rule in the [Philippine–American War](/Philippine%E2%80%93American_War). [Citation needed]

By 1913, the [British Empire](/British_Empire) exerted influence over 412 million people, constituting 23% of the global population at the time. [Citation needed] By 1920, it spanned 35,500,000 km² (13,700,000 sq mi), [Citation needed] accounting for 24% of the Earth's total land area. [Citation needed] At its zenith, the phrase "[the empire on which the sun never sets](/The_empire_on_which_the_sun_never_sets)" aptly described the British Empire, owing to its global expanse ensuring that the sun was always shining on at least one of its territories. [Citation needed] Consequently, its political, [legal](/Common_law), [linguistic](/English_language), and [cultural](/Culture_of_the_United_Kingdom) legacy is widespread throughout the Western world. [Citation needed] In the [aftermath of the Second World War](/Aftermath_of_the_Second_World_War), decolonization efforts were undertaken by all Western powers under the directives of the [United Nations](/United_Nations) (formerly the [League of Nations](/League_of_Nations)). [Citation needed] Most colonized nations achieved independence by 1960. Great Britain demonstrated ongoing responsibility for the welfare of its former colonies as [member states of the Commonwealth of Nations](/Member_states_of_the_Commonwealth_of_Nations). However, the end of Western colonial imperialism coincided with the rise of Western [neocolonialism](/Neocolonialism) or [economic imperialism](/Economic_imperialism). Multinational corporations emerged, offering "a dramatic refinement of the traditional business enterprise," impacting issues as diverse as national sovereignty, ownership of production means, environmental protection, consumerism, and policies toward organized labor. Although the overt colonial era had concluded, Western nations, as comparatively wealthy, well-armed, and culturally influential states, wielded considerable power globally, often without a commensurate sense of responsibility towards the populations affected by their multinational corporations' exploitation of resources and markets. [Citation needed] [Citation needed] The dictum of [Alfred Thayer Mahan](/Alfred_Thayer_Mahan)—that whoever controls the seas controls the world—continues to hold relevance. [Citation needed]

#### Cold War (1947–1991)

*   Main article: [Cold War](/Cold_War)
*   This section lacks sufficient [citations](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources). Please help [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Western_world) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and [removed](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). (April 2021) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

During the [Cold War](/Cold_War), a new conceptual framework emerged, dividing the world into three "worlds." The [First World](/First_World), in this context, was analogous to the West and comprised [NATO members](/Member_states_of_NATO) and other nations aligned with the United States.

The Second World consisted of the [Eastern Bloc](/Eastern_bloc) within the Soviet [sphere of influence](/Sphere_of_influence), including the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) and Warsaw Pact countries such as [Poland](/Polish_People%27s_Republic), [Bulgaria](/People%27s_Republic_of_Bulgaria), [Hungary](/Hungarian_People%27s_Republic), [Romania](/Socialist_Republic_of_Romania), [East Germany](/German_Democratic_Republic), and [Czechoslovakia](/Czechoslovak_Socialist_Republic).

The Third World encompassed countries, many of which were [unaligned with either the west or the east](/Non-Aligned_Movement). Notable members included India, [Yugoslavia](/Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia), [Finland](/Finland) (through [Finlandization](/Finlandization)), and Switzerland (with its policy of [Swiss Neutrality](/Foreign_relations_of_Switzerland)). Some classifications also include the [People's Republic of China](/People%27s_Republic_of_China), although this is debated due to China's communist alignment and its historically friendly relations with the Soviet bloc at various times, as well as its significant geopolitical influence. Certain Third World countries aligned themselves with either the U.S.-led West or the Soviet-led East.

A number of countries did not fit neatly into this tripartite division, including Switzerland, Sweden, Austria, and [Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland), all of which maintained neutrality. Finland, while under the Soviet Union's military sphere of influence (as stipulated by the [FCMA treaty](/FCMA_treaty)), remained neutral and non-communist. It was not a member of the Warsaw Pact or Comecon but joined the EFTA in 1986 and was situated west of the [Iron Curtain](/Iron_Curtain). Austria, upon regaining full independence in 1955, committed to neutrality but was geographically west of the Iron Curtain and thus within the United States' sphere of influence. Spain did not join NATO until 1982, seven years after the death of the authoritarian leader [Francisco Franco](/Francisco_Franco).

The advent of [Mikhail Gorbachev](/Mikhail_Gorbachev) in the 1980s heralded the end of the Cold War, culminating in the [dissolution of the Soviet Union](/Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union).

### Modern Definitions

*   [Asia](/Asia) (as the "[Eastern world](/Eastern_world)"), the [Arab world](/Arab_world), and [Africa](/Africa).

The precise definition of the "Western world" remains somewhat subjective, varying based on whether cultural, economic, spiritual, or political criteria are applied. A common Western perspective acknowledges the existence of at least three "major worlds" (or "cultures," or "civilizations") in broad contrast to the West: the [Eastern world](/Eastern_world), the [Arab world](/Arab_world), and the [African](/Africa) worlds, without clearly defined boundaries. Furthermore, the [Latin American](/Latin_America) and [Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodoxy_by_country) European worlds are sometimes categorized as either sub-civilizations within Western civilization or as distinct entities "akin" to the West.

*   [Latin America](/Latin_America) and [Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodoxy_by_country) worlds. [Image reference needed]

Many anthropologists, sociologists, and historians reject the simplistic categorization of "the West and the Rest." [Citation needed] This has also been observed among Malthusian demographers who draw a sharp distinction between European and non-European family systems. Prominent anthropologists who have explored these distinctions include [Émile Durkheim](/Durkheim), [Louis Dumont](/Dumont), and [Claude Lévi-Strauss](/Lévi-Strauss). [Citation needed]

#### Cultural Definition

*   Further information: [Western culture](/Western_culture), [Culture of Europe](/Culture_of_Europe), and [Culture of the United States](/Culture_of_the_United_States)

The Oxford English Dictionary notes that the earliest recorded use of the term "Western world" in the English language dates back to 1586, appearing in the writings of [William Warner](/William_Warner_(poet)). [Citation needed]

In contemporary usage, the "Western world" typically refers to [Europe](/Europe) and regions whose populations are predominantly of [European origin](/European_emigration), a demographic shift resulting from the [Age of Discovery's](/Age_of_Discovery) imperialism. [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed]

During the 20th century, Christianity experienced a decline in influence across many Western nations, particularly within the European Union, where several member states have witnessed decreasing church attendance and membership in recent years. [Citation needed] This trend has been accompanied by an increase in [secularism](/Secularism), which advocates for the separation of religion from politics and science. However, despite declining church attendance, in some Western countries (such as Italy, Poland, and Portugal), a majority of the population still identifies religion as important [Importance_of_religion_by_country], and most Westerners nominally identify as Christians (for instance, 59% in the United Kingdom) and observe religious practices on major holidays like Christmas and Easter. In the Americas, Christianity continues to hold significant societal sway, although regions like Canada exhibit lower levels of religiosity due to a process of secularization akin to that in Europe. While the United Kingdom and some Nordic countries maintain official state religions that are forms of Christianity, the majority of European countries have no official religion. Nevertheless, Christianity, in its various forms, remains the predominant faith in most Western nations. [Citation needed]

Christianity continues to be the dominant religion in the Western world, with approximately 70% of the population adhering to it. [Citation needed] A 2011 survey by the [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) indicated that 76.2% of [Europeans](/Europe), 73.3% in [Oceania](/Oceania), and around 86.0% in the [Americas](/Americas) (with 90% in [Latin America and the Caribbean](/Latin_America_and_the_Caribbean) and 77.4% in [Northern America](/Northern_America)) identified themselves as Christians. [Citation needed] [Citation needed]

Since the mid-20th century, the West has become increasingly associated with [irreligious](/Irreligious) sentiments. Following the [Age of Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment) and the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution), [inquisitions](/Inquisition) were abolished in the 19th and 20th centuries. This accelerated the [separation of church and state](/Separation_of_church_and_state) and the [secularization](/Secularization) of the Western world, where unchurched [spirituality](/Spirituality) is gaining prominence over [organized religion](/Organized_religion). [Citation needed]

Certain regions within the Western world have become notably more [diverse](/Cultural_diversity) since the late 1960s. [Citation needed] [Citation needed] Previously, between the 18th century and the mid-20th century, prominent Western countries like the United States, Canada, Brazil, Argentina, Australia, and New Zealand were envisioned by some as [homelands](/Ethnocracy) for [white people](/White_people). [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Racism](/Racism) has been identified as a contributing factor to the [colonization](/Analysis_of_Western_European_colonialism_and_colonization) of the [New World](/New_World) by Westerners, which now constitutes a significant portion of the geographical West. [Citation needed] [Citation needed]

Countries within the Western world are also the most avid adopters of digital and televisual media technologies, mirroring their earlier embrace of television and radio in the postwar period. Between 2000 and 2014, [Internet](/Internet) [market penetration](/Market_penetration) in the West was double that of non-Western regions. [Citation needed]

#### Economic Definition

Countries by income group.
Map of the Western world, including the [Anglosphere](/Anglosphere) (as defined by [James Bennett](/James_Bennett_(journalist))), the [European Union](/European_Union), and [European Single Market](/European_Single_Market) members, 2017.

The term "Western world" is sometimes used interchangeably with "First World" or "developed countries," emphasizing the distinction between the First World and the [Third World](/Third_World) or [developing countries](/Developing_country). This usage persists despite the fact that many culturally Western countries are themselves [developing countries](/Developing_country); in fact, a substantial portion of the Americas falls into this category. It is also used despite numerous [developed countries or regions](/Developed_country) not being culturally Western (e.g., [Japan](/Japan), [Singapore](/Singapore), [South Korea](/South_Korea), [Taiwan](/Taiwan), [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong), and [Macao](/Macao)). [Privatization](/Privatization) policies (involving state-owned enterprises and public services) and the activities of [multinational corporations](/Multinational_corporation) are often seen as indicators of Western economic influence, particularly in Third World countries. These entities represent a common institutional environment for influential politicians, businesses, trade unions, firms, bankers, and thinkers within the Western world. [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed] [Citation needed]

#### Other Views

A number of civilization scholars, including [Arnold J. Toynbee](/Arnold_J._Toynbee), [Alfred Kroeber](/Alfred_Kroeber), and [Carroll Quigley](/Carroll_Quigley), have identified and analyzed "Western civilization" as one of the [civilizations](/Civilization) that have historically existed and continue to exist today. Toynbee's approach was notably expansive, including as candidates those countries or cultures that became so profoundly influenced by the West as to integrate these borrowings into their very self-identity. Taken to its extreme, this definition would encompass nearly everyone within the West, in various ways. Toynbee specifically refers to the intelligentsia formed among the educated elites of nations impacted by centuries of European expansion. While often exhibiting a strong nationalist sentiment, these cultural and political leaders interacted with the West to such an extent that they transformed both themselves and the West. [Citation needed]

The [theologian](/Theologian) and [paleontologist](/Paleontologist) [Pierre Teilhard de Chardin](/Pierre_Teilhard_de_Chardin) conceived of the West as the collection of civilizations descended from the [Nile Valley Civilization](/Nile_Valley_Civilizations) of [Egypt](/Egypt). [Citation needed]

The concept of "the West" has evolved over time from a directional designation to a sociopolitical construct, temporalized and framed as a vision of the future imbued with notions of progress and modernity. [Citation needed]

