*   ^ In relation to Rome's central geographic position within the Empire, "West" and "East" denoted provinces situated to the west and east of the capital, respectively. Consequently, [Iberia](/Iberian_Peninsula) (Portugal and Spain), [Gaul](/Gaul) (France), the Mediterranean coast of [North Africa](/North_Africa) (Tunisia, Algeria, and Morocco), and [Britannia](/Britannia) were all considered part of the "West." Greece, Cyprus, Anatolia, Lebanon, Syria, Israel, Palestine, Egypt, and Libya belonged to the "East." Italy itself was considered central until the reforms of [Diocletian](/Diocletian), which divided the Empire into distinct Eastern and Western halves. [Citation needed]
*   ^ Portuguese sailors began exploring the coast of Africa and the Atlantic archipelagos in 1418–19, utilizing recent advancements in navigation, cartography, and maritime technology such as the [caravel](/Caravel), in their quest to discover a sea route to the source of the lucrative [spice trade](/Spice_trade). [Citation needed] In 1488, [Bartolomeu Dias](/Bartolomeu_Dias), sponsored by Portugal's [John II](/John_II_of_Portugal), rounded the southern tip of Africa, observing that the coast then turned northeast ([Cape of Good Hope](/Cape_of_Good_Hope)). [Citation needed]
    In 1492, [Christopher Columbus](/Christopher_Columbus) landed on an island in the [Bahamas archipelago](/The_Bahamas) on behalf of the Spanish crown. Documentation of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean)'s routes led to him being granted a [coat of arms](/Coat_of_arms) by [Pope Alexander VI](/Pope_Alexander_VI) *motu proprio* in 1502. [Citation needed]
    With the discovery of the American continent, or '[New World](/New_World)', in 1492–1493, the European colonial [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery) and exploration was initiated. This era revisited an [imperialistic](/Imperialism) perspective, amplified by the invention of [firearms](/History_of_gunpowder), and marked the beginning of the [Modern Era](/Modern_Era). During this extended period, the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) undertook a significant effort to propagate Christianity in the New World and convert the [Native Americans](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) and others. A 'Modern West' emerged from the [Late Middle Ages](/Late_Middle_Ages) (following the Renaissance and the fall of Constantinople) as a new civilization deeply influenced by the interpretation of Greek thought preserved in the Byzantine Empire and transmitted through Latin [translations](/Latin_translations_of_the_12th_century) and the [emigration of Greek scholars](/Greek_scholars_in_the_Renaissance) via [Renaissance humanism](/Renaissance_humanism). (Popular [typefaces](/Typefaces) such as [italics](/Italics) were inspired by and designed from transcriptions during this period.) [Renaissance architectural](/Renaissance_architecture) works and [revivals](/Revivalism_(architecture)) of [Classical](/Classical_architecture) and [Gothic](/Gothic_architecture) styles flourished throughout [Western colonial empires](/History_of_architecture) during this modern period.
    In 1497, Portuguese navigator [Vasco da Gama](/Vasco_da_Gama) completed the first direct sea voyage from Europe to India. [Citation needed]
    In 1520, [Ferdinand Magellan](/Ferdinand_Magellan), a Portuguese navigator serving the [Crown of Castile](/Crown_of_Castile) ('[Spain](/Spain)'), discovered a sea route into the [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean).
*   ^ In the 16th century, the Portuguese disrupted the existing (overland) medieval monopoly held by Arabs and Italians on trade (including goods and slaves) between Asia and [Europe](/Europe) by [discovering the sea route to India](/Discovery_of_the_sea_route_to_India) around the Cape of Good Hope. [Citation needed] With the subsequent rise of the rival Dutch East India Company, Portuguese influence in Asia gradually waned; Dutch forces first established fortified independent bases in the East and then, between 1640 and 1660, wrested control of several southern Indian ports and the lucrative [Japan](/Japan) trade from the Portuguese. Later, the [English](/English_people) and the [French](/France) established settlements in [India](/India) and engaged in trade with [China](/China), gradually surpassing the Dutch in their acquisitions. By 1763, the British had eliminated French influence in India and established the [British East India Company](/British_East_India_Company) as the dominant political force on the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent).
*   ^ The [Scramble for Africa](/Scramble_for_Africa) refers to the occupation, division, and colonization of African territory by European powers during the period of [New Imperialism](/New_Imperialism), between 1881 and 1914. It is also known as the 'Partition of Africa' and, by some, the 'Conquest of Africa'. In 1870, only 10 percent of Africa was under formal Western/European control; by 1914, this had increased to almost 90 percent of the continent, with only the [Ethiopian Empire](/Ethiopian_Empire) (Abyssinia), the [Dervish state](/Dervish_state) (a portion of present-day [Somalia](/Somalia)), [Citation needed] and [Liberia](/Liberia) remaining independent.
*   ^ In [ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece) (8th century BC – AD 6th century), hegemony signified the politico-military dominance of one [city-state](/City-state) over others. [Citation needed] The dominant state was known as the hegemon. [Citation needed] [136]

